## Backend Search Implementation

### Text Search

```
Level 1: LIKE / regex (simple, limited)
  WHERE name ILIKE '%john%'
  { name: { $regex: "john", $options: "i" } }
  Pros: Simple, no setup
  Cons: Slow on large datasets, no relevance ranking

Level 2: Full-text index (database-native)
  MongoDB: Text index + $text query
  PostgreSQL: tsvector + ts_query
  MySQL: FULLTEXT index
  Pros: Fast, supports stemming and stop words
  Cons: Limited relevance ranking, language-dependent

Level 3: Dedicated search engine (best UX)
  Elasticsearch, Meilisearch, Typesense, Algolia
  Pros: Fast, typo-tolerant, faceted, ranked, highlights
  Cons: Extra infrastructure, data sync required
```

### Which to Use

**Principle:** Choose your search backend based on dataset size and query complexity - start simple and scale up only when needed.

[REFERENCE] Typical backend tiers by dataset size:

```
< 10,000 records:     Level 1 (regex/LIKE) is fine
10,000 - 1,000,000:   Level 2 (full-text index) recommended
> 1,000,000:           Level 3 (dedicated search engine) recommended - strong DB FTS with good indexing can handle millions for simple search
Complex search needs:  Level 3 regardless of size (typo tolerance, faceting, synonyms)
```

### Search Endpoint Design

```
GET /api/resources?search=john&status=active&group=alpha&sort=name&dir=asc&page=1&limit=20

Response:
{
  "records": [
    { "id": "...", "name": "John Doe", "group": {...}, ... }
  ],
  "pagination": {
    "page": 1,
    "limit": 20,
    "total": 3,
    "totalPages": 1
  },
  "filters": {
    "search": "john",
    "status": "active",
    "group": "alpha"
  }
}
```

### Server-Side Rules

- **Sanitize search input** - strip special regex/query characters to prevent injection
- **Limit search length** - max 200 characters (prevent massive regex/query payloads)
- **Index searchable fields** - EVERY field used in WHERE/filter MUST have an index
- **Combine search + filters server-side** - search narrows within the filtered set, not separately
- **Case-insensitive** by default for text search
- **Trim whitespace** before searching

